article.headline: Denver 105, Phoenix 92
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Denver Nuggets are no longer one of the bottom feeders in the West. They've passed that label to the Phoenix Suns. Voshon Lenard scored 32 points and the Nuggets handed the Suns their sixth loss in a row, 105-92 Tuesday night. The one-sided victory was sandwiched between Denver's games against Western powerhouses Sacramento and the Los Angeles Lakers. The Nuggets play at Los Angeles Wednesday night. "I get tired of people who keep telling me how down the Nuggets were last year," rookie Carmelo Anthony said. "They can talk about how we're playing right now. Any team we play, we go in with the mentality that we can beat them." The Nuggets scored the first nine points, led by 17 in the first quarter, 21 at the half and 32 in the third quarter against the hapless Suns -- 0-4 since the blockbuster trade that sent Stephon Marbury to the New York Knicks. "They've been struggling lately. I'm glad they were struggling when we came in," Lenard said. "They didn't have the confidence they had a few weeks ago. We caught them on a good night." Marcus Camby had 16 points and 17 rebounds for Denver, which improved to 23-16. Earl Boykins added 16 points, and Carmelo Anthony 13. Andre Miller had 11 points and 11 assists. "We owe it to free agency over the summer," Camby said. "Management did a good job of getting the players in here that we need, and so far it seems to be working." Amare Stoudemire, in his second game back after missing 18 games with a high ankle sprain, scored 28 points -- all in the second half after playing just five minutes in the first because of foul trouble. Shawn Marion added 23 points and Zarko Cabarkapa 14 for Phoenix. "We're not looking too good right now," Stoudemire said. "I know the fans are kind of upset, but all we can do is go out there and give it our all, practice hard and try to transfer it over to the games." Lenard's inside basket gave Denver its biggest lead, 87-55, with 3:15 left in the third quarter. Phoenix had a 21-6 run to cut it to 93-76 on Cabarkapa's layup with 8:21 to play, and the 13-point final margin was as close the Suns got in the second half. Suns coach Mike D'Antoni said his team came out lifeless after three days of energetic practices. "No excuses except we didn't play hard enough at first," D'Antoni said. "We're going to make a lot of mistakes, but if we play hard, we'll be OK. Otherwise, we're going to be in for a long night -- and it was a long night." The Nuggets' 8-10 road record matches their best start ever away from home. They last accomplished it in 1987-88. "I'm not sure what that's saying to be honest with you, because we have a long ways to go," coach Jeff Bzdelik said. "The most important thing is our game tomorrow in L.A., just take it one day at a time and keep getting better." Denver led 34-15 after Chris Andersen's two free throws to start the second quarter. Joe Johnson's fast-break stuff capped an 8-0 run that cut it to 38-29, and Marion's six-footer made it 43-34 with 4:43 to go in the half. But the Nuggets responded with a 14-2 outburst to go up 57-36 at the break. Denver scored the last nine points of the half, four by Anthony. The Suns made two of their first 13 shots and committed six turnovers as Denver shot out to a 20-4 lead. The lead increased to 28-10 on Andersen's 17-footer with 2:11 left in the first.

Game notes
Lenard had his third 30-point game of the season. ... The Suns, who had 18 turnovers for 28 Nuggets' points, committed 26 turnovers in their 110-80 loss at Denver on Nov. 25. ... The Suns are 4-13 since D'Antoni replaced Frank Johnson as coach. ... Phoenix starting center Jake Voskuhl missed the game because of the birth of his second daughter, Skylar Joy, earlier in the day. ... Denver still is just 16-43 at America West Arena.
